<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-215-138  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 215 138.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 5 1990 v7 n10 p13(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Chiquita power-line net monitors bananas. (Chiquita BrandsInc.)(monitoring networks are installed on cargo ships)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Chiquita Brands Inc is installing a monitoring network on cargoships that will automate the maintenance of the particularenvironment needed for the preservation of perishable food items.andO;Data is transmitted from refrigerated containers to an on-boardmicrocomputer over electrical power lines.andP;  An alarm goes off whenthe temperature or humidity of any particular unit changes.andO;Commands for regulating the container's atmosphere can beimmediately downloaded, so crew members no longer need to performthese monitoring tasks manually.andP;  A power-line transmissiontechnology recommended as a draft standard by the InternationalStandards Organization (ISO) is used by the monitoring system.andO;Controllers and modems are installed in refrigerated containers,the controllers monitor the atmosphere and adjust the unit'soperation and the modem transmits data over an alternating current(AC) power line.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Chiquita Brands Inc. (automation).andO;Topic:     Cargo HandlingNetworksPower SupplyRefrigeration EquipmentTransportationFood Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Shipping data over power lines. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>